No, the provided code is not suitable for a static library. It is specifically designed to load and execute functions from a dynamic/shared library (DLL on Windows).

To use a static library, you don't need to use functions like `LoadLibraryA` or `GetProcAddress` to dynamically load and call functions from the library. Instead, you can simply link the static library at compile-time and directly call the functions.

Here's an example of how you can modify the code to use a static library:

```cpp
#include "test.h" // Include the header file for the static library

int main(int ac, char *av[])
{
    // Call the function from the static library
    loop();

    return 0;
}
```

Make sure to include the correct header file (`test.h` in this case) from the static library and link the static library during the compilation process. Additionally, you may need to adjust the project settings to properly link the static library in your development environment.

