No, the `dlopen` function is not available on Windows. It is a function provided by the POSIX standard for dynamically loading shared libraries in Unix-based systems.

On Windows, you can use the `LoadLibrary` function from the Windows API to dynamically load a DLL (Dynamic-Link Library). Here's an example of how you can use `LoadLibrary` on Windows:

```cpp
#include <windows.h>
#include <iostream>

int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    typedef void (ProcessDataFunc)();

    HMODULE libHandle = LoadLibraryA("lib.dll"); // Load the library
    if (libHandle != NULL) {
        ProcessDataFunc* loop = (ProcessDataFunc*)GetProcAddress(libHandle, "loop");
        if (loop != NULL) {
            std::cout << "in\n";
            loop(); // Call the function
        }
    }

    if (libHandle != NULL) {
        FreeLibrary(libHandle); // Free the library
    }

    return 0;
}
```

Remember to replace "lib.dll" with the correct name of your DLL file. Additionally, ensure that the DLL file is present in the same directory as the executable or specify the full path if it is located elsewhere.

Also, note that when using `LoadLibrary` on Windows, you need to use `GetProcAddress` to obtain the function pointer of the exported function from the DLL.

